<section xml:id="section-slope">
  <title>Slope</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      A steady, constant rate of change has a special name, <em>slope</em>, and we'll explore slope
      more in this section.
    </p>

    <!-- <figure>
      <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
      <video youtubeplaylist="PLmuZCPhWPt-ehhIZJSr3Tp7xyA450Od5R" />
    </figure> -->
  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>Modeling data with two variables</title>
    <p>
      Math helps us understand data from the world around us. Then we can use what we discover to
      make good decisions. Here's an example with economic data from the US, plotted in a Cartesian
      plane.
    </p>

    <p>
      For the years from 2000 to 2025, consider what percent of American wealth was held by the
      wealthiest 1% of Americans. The table in <xref ref="figure-top-one-percent"/> gives the
      numbers (source:
      <url href="https://www.federalreserve.gov/releases/z1/dataviz/dfa/distribute/table/" visual="federalreserve.gov"/>),
      but any pattern there might not be apparent when looking at the data organized this way. 
      Plotting the data in a Cartesian coordinates system can make an overall pattern or trend
      become visible.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-top-one-percent">
      <caption>Share of all income held by the top 1% of wage earners</caption>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 50%" margins="0%">
        <tabular>
          <col/>
          <col right="medium"/>
          <col/>
          <col/>
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell>year</cell><cell>%</cell>
            <cell>year</cell><cell>%</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2000</cell><cell>27.4</cell>
            <cell>2013</cell><cell>29.8</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2001</cell><cell>25.9</cell>
            <cell>2014</cell><cell>30.4</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2002</cell><cell>25.3</cell>
            <cell>2015</cell><cell>30.7</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2003</cell><cell>25.4</cell>
            <cell>2016</cell><cell>30.7</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2004</cell><cell>26.8</cell>
            <cell>2017</cell><cell>30.7</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2005</cell><cell>27.2</cell>
            <cell>2018</cell><cell>30.5</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2006</cell><cell>28.0</cell>
            <cell>2019</cell><cell>30.6</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2007</cell><cell>28.8</cell>
            <cell>2020</cell><cell>29.9</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2008</cell><cell>28.2</cell>
            <cell>2021</cell><cell>30.8</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2009</cell><cell>27.8</cell>
            <cell>2022</cell><cell>29.8</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2010</cell><cell>28.4</cell>
            <cell>2023</cell><cell>30.1</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2011</cell><cell>29</cell>
            <cell>2024</cell><cell>30.7</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>2012</cell><cell>29.5</cell>
            <cell>2025</cell><cell>31.2</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>

        <image>
          <shortdescription>a scatter plot about share of all wealth held by the top 1% in the US</shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="top-1percent-income-scatterplot">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  xlabel={year},
                  ylabel={percentage},
                  xmin=2000,xmax=2030,
                  ymin=0,ymax=40,
                  minor ytick=,
                  axis line style={->},
                  xtick={2000,2005,...,2030},
                  xticklabels={2000,2005,...,2030},
                  xticklabel style={rotate=-45},
                  ytick={0,5,...,40},
                  width=0.5\orccaprintwidth
                ]
                \addplot[only marks]coordinates{
                  (2000, 27.4)
                  (2001, 25.9)
                  (2002, 25.3)
                  (2003, 25.4)
                  (2004, 26.8)
                  (2005, 27.2)
                  (2006, 28)
                  (2007, 28.8)
                  (2008, 28.2)
                  (2009, 27.8)
                  (2010, 28.4)
                  (2011, 29)
                  (2012, 29.5)
                  (2013, 29.8)
                  (2014, 30.4)
                  (2015, 30.7)
                  (2016, 30.7)
                  (2017, 30.7)
                  (2018, 30.5)
                  (2019, 30.6)
                  (2020, 29.9)
                  (2021, 30.8)
                  (2022, 29.8)
                  (2023, 30.1)
                  (2024, 30.7)
                  (2025, 31.2)
                };
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>

    <p>
      What observations do you see now that you couldn't easily see from the numbers in the table?
      Do you see evidence of the COVID pandemic? Evidence of the Great Recession of 2008?
    </p>
    <p>
      Overall, do you see a larger pattern with wealth distribution? Assuming that you see the
      rising pattern, is it easier to see that with the graph than with the table?
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Patterns in Tables</title>
    <example xml:id="example-three-tables">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a pattern in each table, using only the table itself. What is the missing entry in
          each table? Can you describe each pattern in words and/or mathematics?
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="table-patterns-non-math">
          <caption>Patterns in 3 tables</caption>
          <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%"  margins="0%">
            <tabular top="major" bottom="minor" left="major" right="minor">
              <col/>
              <col right="major"/>
              <row>
                <cell>black</cell>
                <cell>white</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>big</cell>
                <cell>small</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>short</cell>
                <cell>tall</cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="major">
                <cell>few</cell>
                <cell/>
              </row>
            </tabular>
            <tabular top="major" bottom="minor" left="major" right="minor">
              <col/>
              <col right="major"/>
              <row>
                <cell>USA</cell>
                <cell>Washington</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>UK</cell>
                <cell>London</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>France</cell>
                <cell>Paris</cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="major">
                <cell>Mexico</cell>
                <cell/>
              </row>
            </tabular>
            <tabular top="major" bottom="minor" left="major" right="minor">
              <col/>
              <col right="major"/>
              <row>
                <cell>1</cell>
                <cell>2</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>2</cell>
                <cell>4</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>3</cell>
                <cell>6</cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="major">
                <cell>5</cell>
                <cell/>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </sidebyside>
        </figure>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <dl>
            <li>
              <title>First table</title>
              <p>
                Each word on the right has the opposite meaning of the word to its left.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>Second table</title>
              <p>
                Each city on the right is the capital of the country to its left.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>Third table</title>
              <p>
                Each number on the right is double the number to its left.
              </p>
            </li>
          </dl>
        </p>
        <figure>
          <caption>Patterns in 3 tables</caption>
          <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" margins="0%">
            <tabular top="major" bottom="minor" left="major" right="minor">
              <col/>
              <col right="major"/>
              <row>
                <cell>black</cell>
                <cell>white</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>big</cell>
                <cell>small</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>short</cell>
                <cell>tall</cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="major">
                <cell>few</cell>
                <cell><em>many</em></cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
            <tabular top="major" bottom="minor" left="major" right="minor">
              <col/>
              <col right="major"/>
              <row>
                <cell>USA</cell>
                <cell>Washington</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>UK</cell>
                <cell>London</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>France</cell>
                <cell>Paris</cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="major">
                <cell>Mexico</cell>
                <cell><em>Mexico City</em></cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
            <tabular top="major" bottom="minor" left="major" right="minor">
              <col/>
              <col right="major"/>
              <row>
                <cell>1</cell>
                <cell>2</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>2</cell>
                <cell>4</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>3</cell>
                <cell>6</cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="major">
                <cell>5</cell>
                <cell><em>10</em></cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </sidebyside>
        </figure>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      Generally in a table with two columns of data, we can think of the table as <em>assigning</em>
      value on the right to each value on the left. The first table <em>assigns</em> <q>white</q> to
      <q>black</q>, as its opposite. The second table <em>assigns</em> <q>Paris</q> to
      <q>France</q>, as its capital city. The third table <em>assigns</em> <m>10</m> to <m>5</m>, as
      its double. 
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="60% 33%" margins="0%">
      <stack>
        <p>
          The third table in <xref ref="example-three-tables"/> is numerical. And its <q>function</q>
          is to take a number as input, and give twice that number as output. Mathematically, we can
          describe the pattern as <q><m>f(x)=2x</m></q>, pronounced <q>f of x equals
          <ellipsis/></q>, where <m>x</m> represents the input and <m>f</m> is the name of the
          process that turns input <m>x</m> into something else. So that <q><m>f(x)</m></q> (again,
          prounounced <q>f of x</q>) represents whatever <m>f</m> turned <m>x</m> into.
          Labeling the table with these symbols, we have <xref ref="figure-pattern-double"/>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The formula <m>f(x)=2x</m> summarizes the pattern in the table.
        </p>
      </stack>
      <figure xml:id="figure-pattern-double">
        <caption>Table with a mathematical pattern</caption>
        <tabular>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell>
              <line><m>x</m></line>
              <line>(input)</line></cell>
            <cell>
              <line><m>f(x)</m></line>
              <line>(output)</line></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
            <cell><m>4</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
            <cell><m>6</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>5</m></cell>
            <cell><m>10</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell><m>10</m></cell>
            <cell><m>20</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell colspan="2">Pattern: <m>f(x)=2x</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </figure>
    </sidebyside>
    <p>
      Only the third table in <xref ref="example-three-tables"/> is a table of numbers. Let's
      examine that data graphically.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>The data from the third table in <xref ref="example-three-tables"/></caption>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <image>
          <latex-image label="third-table">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  xmin=0,
                  ymin=0,
                  ymax=12,
                  xtick={1,...,7},
                  ytick={1,...,12},
                  minor xtick=,
                  minor ytick=,
                  axis line style={->},
                  width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                  ylabel={\(f(x)\)}
                ]
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1, 2) (2,4) (3,6)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <image>
          <latex-image label="third-table-completed">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  xmin=0,
                  ymin=0,
                  ymax=12,
                  xtick={1,...,7},
                  ytick={1,...,12},
                  minor xtick=,
                  minor ytick=,
                  axis line style={->},
                  width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                  ylabel={\(f(x)\)}
                ]
                \addplot[guideline, dashed, ->] coordinates {(1,2) (4.5,9)};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1, 2) (2,4) (3,6) (5,10)};
                \addplot[guideline, dashed, ->] coordinates {(5,0) (5,9)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>
      With the data plotted, and the question being what should happen when <m>x</m> is <m>5</m>,
      our eyes can converge to the point <m>(5,10)</m> and we conclude the missing value will be
      <m>10</m>. Graphically, we can see the missing output value should be <m>10</m> without
      directly using the formula.
    </p>
    <p>
      For each of the following tables, find an equation that describes the pattern you see. Use
      <q>function notation</q> (<m>f(x)</m>) where appropriate. Numerical pattern recognition may or
      may not come naturally for you and you may want to use a graph to help visually process the
      numbers. Either way, pattern recognition is an important mathematical skill that anyone can
      develop. The solutions for these exercises offer some hints about what patterns you might look
      for.
    </p>
    <exercise label="pattern-from-table-1">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          @x = (0..3);
          $f = Formula("x + 10");
          @y = map{$f->eval(x => $_)}(@x);
          Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y => 'Real');
          parser::Assignment->Allow;
          parser::Assignment->Function("f");
          $eq = Formula("f(x) = $f");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write an equation in the form <m>f(x)=\ldots</m> suggested by the pattern in the table.
          </p>
          <tabular >
            <col halign="right"/>
            <col halign="left"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[0]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[0]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[1]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[1]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[2]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[2]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[3]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[3]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          <p>
            <var name="$eq" width="20"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            One approach to pattern recognition is to look for a relationship in each row. Here,
            the output value in each row is always <m>10</m> more than the <m>x</m>-value. So the
            pattern is described by the equation <m><var name="$eq"/></m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="exercise-linear-data" label="pattern-from-table-2">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          @x = (0..3);
          $f = Formula("-1 + 3x");
          @y = map{$f->eval(x => $_)} (@x);
          Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y => 'Real');
          parser::Assignment->Allow;
          parser::Assignment->Function("f");
          $eq=Formula("f(x) = $f")->reduce;
          @t = map{$_*3} (@x);
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write an equation in the form <m>f(x)=\ldots</m> suggested by the pattern in the table.
          </p>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="right"/>
            <col halign="left"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[0]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[0]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[1]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[1]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[2]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[2]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[3]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[3]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          <p>
            <var name="$eq" width="20"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The relationship between <m>x</m> and the output in each row is not as clear here.
            Another popular approach for finding patterns: in each column, consider how the values
            change from one row to the next. From row to row, the <m>x</m>-value increases by
            <m>1</m>. Also, the output value increases by <m>3</m> from row to row.
          </p>
          <tabular >
            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
            <col halign="left"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[0]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[0]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>(add <m>1</m> from previous) <m><var name="$x[1]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[1]"/></m> (add <m>3</m> from previous)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>(add <m>1</m> from previous) <m><var name="$x[2]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[2]"/></m> (add <m>3</m> from previous)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>(add <m>1</m> from previous) <m><var name="$x[3]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[3]"/></m> (add <m>3</m> from previous)</cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          <p>
            Since row-to-row change is always <m>1</m> for <m>x</m> and is always <m>3</m> for
            output, the <em>rate of change</em> from one row to another row is always the same:
            <m>3</m> units of output for every <m>1</m> unit of <m>x</m>. This suggests that
            <m>f(x)=3x</m> <em>might</em> be a good equation for the table pattern. But if we try to
            make a table with that pattern:
          </p>
          <tabular halign="center">
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>3x</m></cell>
              <cell>Actual value of <m>f(x)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[0]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$t[0]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[0]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[1]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$t[1]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[1]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[2]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$t[2]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[2]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[3]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$t[3]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[3]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          <p>
            We find that the values from <m>f(x)=3x</m> are too large by <m>1</m>. So now we make an
            adjustment. The equation <m><var name="$eq"/></m> describes the pattern in the
            table.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="pattern-from-table-3">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          @x = (0..3);
          $f = Formula("x^2");
          @y = map{$f->eval(x => $_)} (@x);
          Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y => 'Real');
          parser::Assignment->Allow;
          parser::Assignment->Function("f");
          $eq = Formula("f(x) = $f");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Write an equation in the form <m>f(x)=\ldots</m> suggested by the pattern in the table.
          </p>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="right"/>
            <col halign="left"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[0]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[0]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[1]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[1]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[2]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[2]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[3]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[3]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          <p>
            <var name="$eq" width="20"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Looking for a relationship in each row here, we see that each output value is the
            square of the corresponding <m>x</m>-value. That may not be obvious to you. It comes
            down to recognizing what square numbers are. So the equation is <m><var name="$eq"/></m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            What if we had tried the approach we used in the previous exercise, comparing change
            from row to row in each column?
          </p>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="right"/>
            <col halign="left"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[0]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[0]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>(add <m>1</m> from previous) <m><var name="$x[1]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[1]"/></m> (add <m>1</m> from previous)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>(add <m>1</m> from previous) <m><var name="$x[2]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[2]"/></m> (add <m>3</m> from previous)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>(add <m>1</m> from previous) <m><var name="$x[3]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[3]"/></m> (add <m>5</m> from previous)</cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          <p>
            Here, the rate of change is <em>not</em> constant from one row to the next. While the
            <m>x</m>-values are increasing by <m>1</m> from row to row, the output values increase
            more and more from row to row. Do you notice that there is a pattern there as well?
            Mathematicians are interested in finding patterns and describing them.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Rate of Change</title>                                                                             <idx><h>Rate of change</h></idx>
    <p>
      For an hourly wage-earner, the amount of money they earn depends on how many hours they work.
      If a worker earns <m>\$15</m> per hour, then <m>10</m> hours of work corresponds to
      <m>\$150</m> of pay. Working <em>one</em> additional hour will change <m>10</m> hours to
      <m>11</m> hours; and this will cause the <m>\$150</m> in pay to rise by <em>fifteen</em>
      dollars to <m>\$165</m> in pay. Any time we compare how one amount changes (dollars earned)
      as a consequence of another amount changing (hours worked), we are talking about a
      <term>rate of change</term>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Given a table of two-variable data, between any two rows we can compute a <term>rate of
      change</term>.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="example-cancer-data">
      <p>
        The following data, given in both table and graphed form, gives the counts of cancer
        diagnoses in Oregon over a period of time.
        (<url href="https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ph/diseasesconditions/chronicdisease/datareports/pages/cancer-incidence.aspx" visual="oregon.gov/oha/ph/diseasesconditions/chronicdisease/datareports/pages/cancer-incidence.aspx"/>)
      </p>
      <tabular valign="top">
        <col/>
        <col halign="center" right="minor"/>
        <col/>
        <col halign="center"/>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell>Year</cell>
          <cell>Cancer Incidents</cell>
          <cell>Year</cell>
          <cell>Cancer Incidents</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>2007</cell><cell>19,417</cell><cell>2015</cell><cell>22,158</cell></row>
        <row><cell>2008</cell><cell>20,426</cell><cell>2016</cell><cell>22,135</cell></row>
        <row><cell>2009</cell><cell>19,979</cell><cell>2017</cell><cell>23,052</cell></row>
        <row><cell>2010</cell><cell>19,861</cell><cell>2018</cell><cell>22,769</cell></row>
        <row><cell>2011</cell><cell>20,851</cell><cell>2019</cell><cell>24,389</cell></row>
        <row><cell>2012</cell><cell>20,426</cell><cell>2020</cell><cell>21,766</cell></row>
        <row><cell>2013</cell><cell>21,346</cell><cell>2021</cell><cell>22,750</cell></row>
        <row><cell>2014</cell><cell>21,683</cell><cell>2022</cell><cell>22,691</cell></row>
      </tabular>
      <image width="100%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="invasive-cancer-scatterplot">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}[
                xlabel={year},
                ylabel={count},
                ytick=,
                xmin=2005,
                xmax=2025,
                ymin=15000,
                ymax=26000,
                axis line style={->},
                xtick={2005,2010,...,2025},
                xticklabels={2005,2010,...,2025},
                xticklabel style={rotate=-45},
                axis y discontinuity=crunch,
                width=\orccaprintwidth,
                height=0.33\orccaprintwidth,
              ]
              \addplot[only marks] coordinates {
                (2007,19417)
                (2008,20426)
                (2009,19979)
                (2010,19861)
                (2011,20851)
                (2012,20426)
                (2013,21346)
                (2014,21683)
                (2015,22158)
                (2016,22135)
                (2017,23052)
                (2018,22769)
                (2019,24389)
                (2020,21766)
                (2021,22750)
                (2022,22691)
              };
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        Note the drop in 2020 is possibly explained by under-diagnosing, when people were in COVID
        quarantine at home and it was difficult to see a doctor for things like a cancer screening.
      </p>
      <p>
        What was the <term>rate of change</term> in Oregon cancer diagnoses between 2007 and 2010?
        The total (net) change in diagnoses over that timespan is
        <md>
          19861 - 19417 = 444
        </md>
        meaning that there were <m>444</m> more cancer incidents in 2010 than in 2007. Since
        <m>3</m> years passed (which you can calculate as <m>2010-2007</m>), the rate of change is
        <m>444</m> diagnoses per <m>3</m> years, or
        <md>
          \frac{444\,\text{diagnoses}}{3\,\text{year}}=148\,\frac{\text{diagnoses}}{\text{year}}
        </md>
        We read that last quantity as <q><m>148</m> diagnoses per year</q>. This rate of change
        means that between the years <m>2007</m> and <m>2010</m>, there were <m>148</m> more
        diagnoses <em>each</em> year, on average. This is just an average over those three
        years<mdash/>it does not mean that the diagnoses grew by exactly this much each year.
      </p>
    </example>
    <exercise xml:id="exercise-cancer-data" label="cancer-data">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
            @x = (2007..2022);
            @y = (19417,20426,19979,19861,20851,20426,21346,21683,22158,22135,23052,22769,24389,21766,22750,22691);
            %f = map{$_ => $y[$_ - 2007]} (@x);
            $r[0] = ($f{2017} - $f{2007})/(2017 - 2007);
            $r[1] = ($f{2022} - $f{2018})/(2019 - 2010);
            $newUnits = [
              {name => 'diagnoses'},
              {name => 'year', conversion => {factor => 365*24*60*60, s => 1}},
              {name => 'years', conversion => {factor => 365*24*60*60, s => 1}},
              {name => 'yr', conversion => {factor => 365*24*60*60, s => 1}},
              {name => 'yrs', conversion => {factor => 365*24*60*60, s => 1}},
              {name => 'y', conversion => {factor => 365*24*60*60, s => 1}},
            ];
            $rate[0] = NumberWithUnits("$r[0] diagnoses/yr", {newUnit => $newUnits});
            $rate[1] = NumberWithUnits("$r[1] diagnoses/yr", {newUnit => $newUnits});
        </pg-code>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use the data in <xref ref="example-cancer-data"/> to find the rate of change in Oregon
              cancer diagnoses between 2007 and 2017.
            </p>
            <instruction>
              You can type the unit as <c>diagnoses/yr</c>.
            </instruction>
            <p>
              <var name="$rate[0]" width="10"/>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              To find the rate of change between 2007 and 2017, calculate
              <md>
                \frac{23052 - 19417}{2017 - 2007} = 363.5
              </md>.
              So the rate of change was <m><var name="$rate[0]"/></m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              And what was the rate of change between 2018 and 2012?
            </p>
            <p>
              <var name="$rate[1]" width="10"/>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              To find the rate of change between 2018 and 2022, calculate
              <md>
                \frac{22691 - 22769}{2022 - 2018} = -19.5
              </md>.
              So the rate of change was <m><var name="$rate[1]"/></m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      We are ready to give a formal definition for <q>rate of change</q>. Considering our work from
      <xref ref="example-cancer-data"/> and <xref ref="exercise-cancer-data"/>, we settle on:
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="definition-rate-of-change">
      <title>Rate of Change</title>                                                                           <idx><h>Rate of change</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\left(x_1,y_1\right)</m> and <m>\left(x_2,y_2\right)</m> are two data points from a
          set of two-variable data, then the <term>rate of change</term> between them is
          <md>
            \frac{\text{change in $y$}}{\text{change in $x$}}=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}
          </md>.
          The Greek letter delta, <m>\Delta</m>, is used to represent <q>change in</q> since it is
          the first letter of the Greek word for <q>difference</q>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="example-cancer-data"/> and <xref ref="exercise-cancer-data"/> we found three
      rates of change. <xref ref="figure-cancer-data"/> highlights the three pairs of points that
      were used to make these calculations.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="figure-cancer-data">
      <caption/>
      <image width="100%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="invasive-cancer-scatterplot-with-segments">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}[
                xlabel={year},
                ylabel={count},
                ytick=,
                xmin=2005,
                xmax=2025,
                ymin=15000,
                ymax=26000,
                axis line style={->},
                xtick={2000,2005,...,2025},
                xticklabels={2000,2005,...,2025},
                xticklabel style={rotate=-45},
                axis y discontinuity=crunch,
                clip=false,
                width=\orccaprintwidth,
                height=0.33\orccaprintwidth,
              ]
              \addplot[only marks] coordinates{
                (2007,19417)
                (2008,20426)
                (2009,19979)
                (2010,19861)
                (2011,20851)
                (2012,20426)
                (2013,21346)
                (2014,21683)
                (2015,22158)
                (2016,22135)
                (2017,23052)
                (2018,22769)
                (2019,24389)
                (2020,21766)
                (2021,22750)
                (2022,22691)
              };
              \addplot[-] coordinates {(2007,19417) (2010,19861)} node[pos=0.5, pin=-45:{rate \(444\,\frac{\text{diagnoses}}{\text{year}}\)}]{};
              \addplot[-] coordinates {(2007,19417) (2017,23052)} node[pos=0.5, pin=90:{rate \(363.5\,\frac{\text{diagnoses}}{\text{year}}\)}]{};
              \addplot[-] coordinates {(2018,22769) (2022,22691)} node[pos=0.5, pin=-90:{rate \(-19.5\,\frac{\text{diagnoses}}{\text{year}}\)}]{};
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Note how the larger the numerical rate of change between two points, the steeper the line is
      that connects them. Also in the third calculation, when the <m>y</m>-values moved down as you
      read the graph from left to right, the rate of change was negative. This is such an important
      observation, we'll put it in an official remark.
    </p>
    <remark>
      <p>
        The rate of change between two data points is related to the steepness of the line segment
        that connects those points.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The steeper the line, the larger the rate of change, and vice versa.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If one rate of change between two data points equals another rate of change between
              two different data points, then the corresponding line segments will have the same steepness.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              We always measure rate of change from left to right. When a line segment between two
              data points slants up from left to right, the rate of change between those points will
              be positive. When a line segment between two data points slants down from left to
              right, the rate of change between those points will be negative.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </remark>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
      <p>
        In the solution to <xref ref="exercise-linear-data"/>, the key observation was that the rate
        of change from one row to the next was constant: <m>3</m> units of increase in <m>y</m> for
        every <m>1</m> unit of increase in <m>x</m>. Graphing this pattern in
        <xref ref="figure-linear-data"/>, we see that every line segment here has the same steepness,
        so the whole picture is a straight line.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="figure-linear-data">
        <caption/>
        <image>
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="consistent-rate-of-change">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  ymin=-5,
                  ymax=9,
                  ytick={-4,2,...,8},
                  minor ytick={-5,-4,...,9},
                  width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                  height=0.40\orccaprintwidth,
                ]
                \addplot[only marks]coordinates{
                  (0,-1)
                  (1,2)
                  (2,5)
                  (3,8)
                };
                \addplot[firstcurve,-] coordinates {(0,-1) (3,8)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </sidebyside>
    <p>
      Whenever the rate of change is constant no matter which two <m>(x,y)</m>-pairs (or data pairs)
      are chosen from a data set, then you can conclude the graph will be a straight line <em>even
      without making the graph</em>. We call this kind of relationship a <term>linear</term>                  <idx><h>Linear relationship</h></idx>
      relationship. We'll study linear relationships in more detail throughout this chapter. Right            <idx><h>Relationship</h><h>linear</h></idx>
      now in this section, we feel it is important to simply identify if data has a linear
      relationship or not.
    </p>
    <exercise label="is-it-linear-1">
      <webwork>
        <pg-macros>
          <macro-file>parserPopUp.pl</macro-file>
        </pg-macros>
        <pg-code>
            @x = (-8,-5,-2,1);
            @y = (3.1,2.1,1.1,0.1);
            $popup = DropDown(['The relationship is linear','The relationship is not linear'],0);
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Is there a linear relationship in the table?
          </p>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="right"/>
            <col halign="left"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[0]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[0]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[1]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[1]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[2]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[2]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[3]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[3]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          <p>
            <var name="$popup" form="popup"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            From one <m>x</m>-value to the next, the change is always <m>3</m>. From one
            <m>y</m>-value to the next, the change is always <m>-1</m>. So the rate of change is
            always <m>\frac{-1}{3}=-\frac{1}{3}</m>. Since the rate of change is constant, the
            data have a linear relationship.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="is-it-linear-2">
      <webwork>
        <pg-macros>
          <macro-file>parserPopUp.pl</macro-file>
        </pg-macros>
        <pg-code>
            @x = (11,13,15,17);
            @y = (208,210,214,220);
            $popup = DropDown(['The relationship is linear','The relationship is not linear'],1);
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Is there a linear relationship in the table?
          </p>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="right"/>
            <col halign="left"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[0]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[0]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[1]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[1]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[2]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[2]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[3]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[3]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          <p>
            <var name="$popup" form="popup"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The rate of change between the first two points is <m>\frac{210-208}{13-11}=1</m>. The
            rate of change between the last two points is <m>\frac{220-214}{17-15}=3</m>. This is
            one way to demonstrate that the rate of change differs for different pairs of points, so
            this pattern is not linear.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="is-it-linear-3">
      <webwork>
        <pg-macros>
          <macro-file>parserPopUp.pl</macro-file>
        </pg-macros>
        <pg-code>
          @x = (3,6,8,12);
          @y = (-2,-8,-12,-20);
          $popup = DropDown(['The relationship is linear','The relationship is not linear'],0);
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Is there a linear relationship in the table?
          </p>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="right"/>
            <col halign="left"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[0]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[0]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[1]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[1]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[2]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[2]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m><var name="$x[3]"/></m></cell>
              <cell><m><var name="$y[3]"/></m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          <p>
            <var name="$popup" form="popup"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The changes in <m>x</m> from one row to the next are <m>+3</m>,<m>+2</m>, and <m>+8</m>.
            That's not a consistent pattern, but we need to consider rates of change between points.
            The rate of change between the first two points is <m>\frac{-8-(-2)}{6-3}=-2</m>. The
            rate of change between the next two points is <m>\frac{-12-(-8)}{8-6}=-2</m>. And the
            rate of change between the last two points is <m>\frac{-20-(-12)}{12-8}=-2</m>. So the
            rate of change, <m>-2</m>, is constant regardless of which pairs we choose. That means
            these pairs describe a linear relationship.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      Let's return to the data that we opened the section with, in
      <xref ref="figure-top-one-percent"/>. Is that data linear?  Well, yes and no. To be completely
      honest, it's not linear. It's easy to pick out pairs of points where the steepness changes
      from one pair to the next. In other words, the points do not line up into a single straight
      line.
    </p>
    <p>
      However if we step back, there does seem to be an overall upward trend that is captured by the
      line overlaying the data in <xref ref="figure-top-one-percent-with-line"/>. Points on the
      overlaid line <em>do</em> have a linear pattern. Let's estimate the rate of change between
      some pair of points on this line. We are free to use any pair of points to do this, so let's
      make this calculation easier by choosing points we can clearly identify on the graph:
      <m>(2010,28.5)</m> and <m>(2021,31)</m>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="figure-top-one-percent-with-line">
      <caption>Share of all income held by the top 1%, United States, 2000<ndash/>2021</caption>
      <image width="60%">
        <shortdescription>a scatter plot about share of all income held by the top 1% in the US</shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="top-one-percent-scatterplot-with-line">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}[
                xlabel={year},
                ylabel={percentage},
                xmin=2000,xmax=2030,
                ymin=0,ymax=40,
                minor ytick=,
                axis line style={->},
                xtick={2000,2005,...,2030},
                xticklabels={2000,2005,...,2030},
                xticklabel style={rotate=-45},
                ytick={0,5,...,40},
                width=0.5\orccaprintwidth
              ]
              \addplot[only marks]coordinates{
                (2000, 27.4)
                (2001, 25.9)
                (2002, 25.3)
                (2003, 25.4)
                (2004, 26.8)
                (2005, 27.2)
                (2006, 28)
                (2007, 28.8)
                (2008, 28.2)
                (2009, 27.8)
                (2010, 28.4)
                (2011, 29)
                (2012, 29.5)
                (2013, 29.8)
                (2014, 30.4)
                (2015, 30.7)
                (2016, 30.7)
                (2017, 30.7)
                (2018, 30.5)
                (2019, 30.6)
                (2020, 29.9)
                (2021, 30.8)
                (2022, 29.8)
                (2023, 30.1)
                (2024, 30.7)
                (2025, 31.2)
              };
              \addplot[firstcurve,domain = 2000:2025,-,ultra thick]{0.20841*(x - 2012.5) + 28.9846};
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The rate of change between those two points is
      <md>
        \frac{(31-28.5)\,\text{pct. points}}{(2021-2010)\,\text{years}}=\frac{2.5\,\text{pct. points}}{11\,\text{years}}\approx0.227\,\frac{\text{pct. points}}{\text{year}}
      </md>
      So we might say that <em>on average</em>, the rate of change expressed by this data is
      <m>0.227</m> percentage points per year.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>What is slope?</title>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

      <stack>
        <p>
          Given a graph with points plotted, when the rate of change from one point to the next one
          never changes, those points must all be on a straight line as in
          <xref ref="figure-constant-rate-of-change"/>. Instead of saying <q>steady, constant rate
          of change</q>, there is a special word for this.
        </p>
      </stack>

      <figure xml:id="figure-constant-rate-of-change">
        <caption>The rate of change is always <m>1/2</m>.</caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="consistent-rate-of-change-for-slope">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  clip=false,
                  width=0.47\orccaprintwidth
                ]
                \addplot+[] {0.5*x+1};
                \addplot[] coordinates {(-6,-2) (-4,-1)} node[pos=0.50, pin=-60:{rate $\frac{1}{2}$}]{};
                \addplot[] coordinates {(-4,-1) (0,1)} node[pos=0.50, pin=120:{rate $\frac{2}{4}=\frac{1}{2}$}]{};
                \addplot[] coordinates {(0,1) (6,4)} node[pos=0.50, pin=90:{rate $\frac{3}{6}=\frac{1}{2}$}]{};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-6,-2) (-4, -1) (0,1) (6,4)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </sidebyside>

    <definition xml:id="definition-slope">
      <title>Slope</title>                                                                                    <idx><h>Slope</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Slope</h><h>definition</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          When <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are two variables where the rate of change between any two               <idx><h>Slope</h><h>as rate of change</h></idx>
          points is the same no matter which two points are used, we call this common rate of change
          the <term>slope</term>. Since having a constant rate of change means the graph will be a            <idx><h>Slope</h><h>of a line</h></idx>
          straight line, it's also called the <term>slope of the line</term>.                                  <idx><h>Lines</h><h>slope of</h></idx>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Considering the definition for
      <xref ref="definition-rate-of-change" text="custom">rate of change</xref>, this means that
      when <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are two variables where the rate of change between two points is
      always the same, then you can calculate slope, <m>m</m>, by finding two distinct data points
      <m>(x_1,y_1)</m> and <m>(x_2,y_2)</m>, and calculating
      <md number="yes" xml:id="equation-slope-definition">
        m=\frac{\text{change in $y$}}{\text{change in $x$}}=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}
      </md>.
    </p>

    <aside>
      <title>Slope <m>m</m></title>
      <p>
        Why is the letter <m>m</m> used as the symbol for <q>slope</q>? Some believe that it comes
        from the French word <q>monter</q> which means <q>to climb</q>.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p>
      A slope is a rate of change. So if there are units for the horizontal and vertical variables,
      then there will be units for the slope. The slope will be measured in
      <m>\frac{\text{vertical units}}{\text{horizontal units}}</m>. If the slope is nonzero, we say           <idx><h>Linear relationship</h></idx>
      that there is a <term>linear relationship</term> between <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>. When the slope          <idx><h>Relationship</h><h>linear</h></idx>
      is <m>0</m>, we say that <m>y</m> is <term>constant</term> with respect to <m>x</m>.                    <idx><h>Relationship</h><h>constant</h></idx>
    </p>

    <p>
      Here are some scenarios with different slopes. As you read each scenario, note how a slope is
      more meaningful with units.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            If a tree grows <m>2.5</m> feet every year, its rate of change in height is the same
            from year to year. So the height and time have a linear relationship where the slope is
            <quantity>
              <mag>2.5</mag><unit base="foot" /><per base="year" />
            </quantity>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            If a company loses <m>2</m> million dollars every year, its rate of change in reserve
            funds is the same from year to year. So the company's reserve funds and time have a
            linear relationship where the slope is <m>-2</m> million dollars per year.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            If Sakura is an adult who has stopped growing, her rate of change in height is the same
            from year to year<mdash/>it's zero. So the slope is
            <quantity>
              <mag>0</mag><unit base="inch" /><per base="year" />
            </quantity>.
            Sakura's height is constant with respect to time. Since the slope is zero, we don't say
            that Sakura's height and time have a linear relationship.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <remark>
      <p>
        A useful phrase for remembering the definition of slope is <q>rise over run</q>. Here,                <idx><h>Rise over run</h></idx>
        <q>rise</q> refers to <q>change in <m>y</m></q>, and <q>run</q> refers to <q>change in
        <m>x</m></q>. Be careful. As mentioned earlier, in mathematics the horizontal direction
        comes <em>first</em>. The phrase <q>rise over run</q> might make it sound like the vertical
        direction comes first, but that is misleading. (It's a bit awkward to say, but the phrase
        <q>run under rise</q> puts the horizontal change first.)
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example xml:id="example-yaras-savings">
      <title>Yara's Savings</title>
      <p>
        On Dec.<nbsp/>31, Yara had only <m>\$50</m> in her savings account. For the the new year,
        she resolved to deposit <m>\$20</m> into her savings account each week, without withdrawing
        any money from the account. Yara keeps her resolution, and her account balance increases
        steadily by <m>\$20</m> each week. That's a constant rate of change, so her account balance
        has a linear relationship with time, and the slope is
        <m>20\, \frac{\text{dollars}}{\text{wk}}</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        After <m>x</m> weeks have passed, we can model the account balance <m>f(x)</m> (pronounced
        <q>f of x</q>) with a formula. Since Yara started with <m>\$50</m> and adds <m>\$20</m> each
        week, then <m>x</m> weeks later the balance is
        <md number="yes" xml:id="equation-yaras-savings">
          f(x) = 50 + 20x
        </md>
        where <m>f(x)</m> is a dollar amount. Notice that the slope,
        <m>20\,\frac{\text{dollars}}{\text{wk}}</m>, is used as the multiplier for <m>x</m>, the
        number of weeks that have passed.
      </p>

      <p>
        We can also examine Yara's savings using a table as in
        <xref ref="figure-yaras-savings-table"/>.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="figure-yaras-savings-table">
        <caption>Yara's savings</caption>
        <tabular>
          <col halign="right"/>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <col halign="left"/>
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell/>
            <cell>
              <line><m>x</m>, weeks</line>
              <line>since Dec.<nbsp/>31</line></cell>
            <cell>
              <line><m>f(x)</m>, savings account</line>
              <line>balance (dollars)</line></cell>
            <cell/>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell/>
            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
            <cell><m>50</m></cell>
            <cell/>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>increases by <m>1</m><m>\longrightarrow</m></cell>
            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>70</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\longleftarrow</m> increases by <m>20</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>increases by <m>1</m><m>\longrightarrow</m></cell>
            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
            <cell><m>90</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\longleftarrow</m> increases by <m>20</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>increases by <m>2</m><m>\longrightarrow</m></cell>
            <cell><m>4</m></cell>
            <cell><m>130</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\longleftarrow</m> increases by <m>40</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>increases by <m>3</m><m>\longrightarrow</m></cell>
            <cell><m>7</m></cell>
            <cell><m>190</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\longleftarrow</m> increases by <m>60</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>increases by <m>5</m><m>\longrightarrow</m></cell>
            <cell><m>12</m></cell>
            <cell><m>290</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\longleftarrow</m> increases by <m>100</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </figure>

      <p>
        In first rows of the table, we see that when <m>x</m> increases by <m>1</m> (week), then
        <m>f(x)</m> increases by <m>20</m> (dollars). The row-to-row rate of change is
        <m>\frac{20\,\text{dollars}}{1\,\text{wk}} = 20\,\frac{\text{dollars}}{\text{wk}}</m>,
        which we already know is the slope. In any table showing a linear relationship, whenever
        <m>x</m> increases by <m>1</m> unit, <m>f(x)</m> will increase by the slope.
      </p>

      <p>
        In later rows, notice that the change in <m>x</m> is larger than <m>1</m>, but the change in
        <m>f(x)</m> is also larger than <m>20</m>. The changes in <m>f(x)</m> have grown
        proportionally with the changes in <m>x</m> and this keeps the <em>rate</em> of change
        steady. Looking in particular at the last two rows of the table, we see <m>x</m> increases
        by <m>5</m> and <m>f(x)</m> increases by <m>100</m>, which gives a rate of change
        <m>\frac{100\,\text{dollars}}{5\,\text{wk}} = 20\,\frac{\text{dollars}}{\text{wk}}</m>,
        which is once again the value of the slope.
      </p>

      <p>
        On a graph of Yara's savings, we can <q>see</q> the rates of change between consecutive rows
        of the table by using <term>slope triangles</term>. These are right triangles showing how to          <idx><h>Slope</h><h>triangle</h></idx>
        move horizontally, then vertically, to get from one point to another.
      </p>

      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <figure xml:id="figure-yaras-savings">
          <caption>Yara's savings</caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="yaras-savings">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xlabel={weeks},
                    ylabel={savings (in dollars)},
                    xmin=0,xmax=15,
                    ymin=0,ymax=320,
                    xtick={2,4,...,14},
                    minor xtick={1,2,...,15},
                    ytick={100,200,300},
                    minor ytick={20,40,...,320},
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                    axis line style={->},
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain = 0:13,->]{50+20*x};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,50) (1,70) (2,90) (4,130) (7,190) (12,290)};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,50) (1,50) (1,65)};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(1,70) (2,70) (2,85)};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(2,90) (4,90) (4,125)};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(4,130) (7,130) (7,185)};
                  \addplot[guideline,-] coordinates {(7,190) (12,190)} node[pos=0.5,below] {$5$ weeks};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(12,190) (12,285)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90] {$\$100$};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <stack>
          <p>
            The large slope triangle indicates that when <m>5</m> weeks pass, Yara saves
            <m>\$100</m>. This is the rate of change between the last two rows of the table,
            <m>\frac{100}{5} = 20 \, \frac{\text{dollars}}{\text{wk}}</m>. The smaller slope
            triangles indicate, from left to right, the rates of change
            <m>\frac{20\,\text{dollars}}{1\,\text{wk}}</m>, <m>\frac{20\,\text{dollars}}{1\,\text{wk}}</m>,
            <m>\frac{40\,\text{dollars}}{2\,\text{wk}}</m>, and
            <m>\frac{60\,\text{dollars}}{3\,\text{wk}}</m> respectively. All of these rates simplify
            to the slope, <m>20 \, \frac{\text{dollars}}{\text{wk}}</m>.
          </p>
        </stack>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        Every slope triangle on the graph of Yara's savings uses the same angles even though some
        triangles are larger than others. Since the ratio of vertical change to horizontal change is
        always <m>20\, \frac{\text{dollars}}{\text{wk}}</m>. On any graph of any sloped line, we can
        draw a slope triangle and compute slope as <q>rise over run</q>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <note>
      <title>Slope Triangles Above</title>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <p>
          Of course, we could draw a slope triangle on the top side of a line. This slope triangle
          works just as well for identifying <q>rise</q> and <q>run</q>, but it emphasizes vertical
          change before horizontal change. For consistency with mathematical conventions, we will
          usually draw slope triangles that show the horizontal change first, followed by the vertical
          change, as in <xref ref="figure-yaras-savings"/>.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <caption>Yara's savings</caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="yaras-savings-alternate">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xlabel={weeks},
                    ylabel={savings (in dollars)},
                    xmin=0,
                    xmax=15,
                    ymin=0,
                    ymax=320,
                    xtick={2,4,...,14},
                    minor xtick={1,2,...,15},
                    ytick={100,200,300},
                    minor ytick={20,40,...,320},
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                    axis line style={->},
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain = 0:13,->]{50+20*x};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,50) (1,70) (2,90) (4,130) (7,190) (12,290)};
                  \addplot[guideline,-] coordinates {(7,190) (7,290)} node[pos=0.5,above,rotate=90] {$\$100$};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(7,290) (11.5,290)} node[pos=0.5,below] {$5$ weeks};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
    </note>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The following graph of a line models the amount of gas, in gallons, in Kiran's gas tank as
          they drive their car. Find the line's slope, and interpret its meaning in this context.
        </p>

        <figure>
          <caption>Amount of gas in Kiran's gas tank</caption>
          <image width="47%">
            <shortdescription>
              This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,8),(6,6),(9,4)...
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="kirans-gas-tank">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xlabel={hours},
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                    ylabel={gas in gallons},
                    xmin=0,
                    xmax=11,
                    ymin=0,
                    ymax=11,
                    minor ytick={0,1,...,11},
                    minor xtick={0,1,...,11},
                    xtick=,
                    ytick=,
                    axis line style={->},
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain=1:8]{-2/3*x+10};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To find a line's slope using its graph, we first identify two points on it and then draw a
          slope triangle. Naturally, we would want to choose two points whose <m>x</m>- and
          <m>y</m>-coordinates are easy to identify exactly based on the graph. We choose the two
          points where <m>x=3</m> and <m>x=6</m>, because they are right on grid line crossings:
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <figure>
            <caption>A Good Slope Triangle</caption>
            <image>
              <shortdescription>
                This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,8),(6,6),(9,4)...There is a slope
                triangle starting from (3,8), passing (6,8) and ending at (6,6). The label from
                (3,8) to (6,8) is "3 hours"; and the label from (6,8) to (6,6) is "-2 gallons".
              </shortdescription>
              <latex-image label="slope-triangle">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                  \begin{axis}[
                      xlabel={hours},
                      ylabel={gas in gallons},
                      xmin=0,
                      xmax=11,
                      ymin=0,
                      ymax=11,
                      minor ytick={0,1,...,11},
                      minor xtick={0,1,...,11},
                      xtick=,
                      ytick=,
                      width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                      axis line style={->},
                    ]
                    \addplot+[domain=1:8]{-2/3*x+10};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,8) (6,6)};
                    \addplot[guideline,-] coordinates {(3,8) (6,8)} node[pos=0.5,above] {$3$ hours};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,8) (6,6.3)} node[pos=0.5,right] {$-2$ gallon};
                  \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>

          <p>
            Notice that the <em>change</em> in <m>y</m> is negative, because the amount of gas is
            decreasing. Since we chose points with integer coordinates, we can easily calculate the
            slope:
            <md>
              \text{slope}=\frac{-2\,\text{gallons}}{3\,\text{hours}}=-\frac{2}{3}\,\frac{\text{gal}}{\text{h}}
            </md>.
            In the given context, this slope implies gas in the tank is <em>decreasing</em> at the
            rate of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>
            <quantity>
              <unit base="gallon" /><per base="hour" />
            </quantity>.
            Since this slope is written as a fraction, another way to understand it is that Kiran
            is using <m>2</m> gallons of gas every <m>3</m> hours.
          </p>
        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise label="find-slope-from-graph">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("Fraction");
          $m = Fraction(3,8);
          $pt1 = Compute("(0, 2)");
          $pt2 = Compute("(8, 5)");
        </pg-code>      
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the slope of the line.
          </p>
          <instruction>
            If the slope does not exist, enter <c>DNE</c> or <c>NONE</c>.
          </instruction>
          <image width="47%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                    xmin = -4,
                    ymin = -3,
                    xmax = 16,
                    ymax = 9,
                    xtick = {},
                    ytick = {},
                    minor xtick = {-4,...,16},
                    minor ytick = {-3,...,9},
                    grid=both,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain = -4:16] {3/8*x+2};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {$pt1 $pt2};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To find the slope of a line from its graph, we first need to identify two points that
            the line passes through. It is wise to choose points with integer coordinates. For this
            problem, we choose <m><var name="$pt1"/></m> and <m><var name="$pt2"/></m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Next, we sketch a slope triangle and find the <em>rise</em> and <em>run</em>. In the
            sketch below, the rise is <m>3</m> and the run is <m>8</m>.
          </p>
          <image width="47%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                    xmin = -4,
                    ymin = -3,
                    xmax = 16,
                    ymax = 9,
                    xtick = {},
                    ytick = {},
                    minor xtick = {-4,...,16},
                    minor ytick = {-3,...,9},
                    grid=both,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain = -4:16] {3/8*x+2};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {$pt1 $pt2};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {$pt1 (8,2)} node[pos=0.5,below] {\(8\)};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(8,2) $pt2} node[pos=0.5,right] {\(3\)};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {$pt1} node[above left] {\($pt1\)};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {$pt2} node[above left] {\($pt2\)};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <p>
            <md>\text{slope}=\frac{\text{rise}}{\text{run}}=\frac{3}{8}</md>
            This line's slope is <m><var name="$m"/></m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("Fraction");
          $slope = Fraction(3,4);
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Make a table and plot the function <m>f</m>, where <m>f(x)=\frac{3}{4}x+2</m>, which
            makes a straight line. Use the plot to determine the slope of this line.
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$slope" width="10"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            First, we choose some <m>x</m>-values to make a table, and compute the corresponding
            <m>y</m>-values.
          </p>
          <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell halign="center"><m>f(x)=\frac{3}{4}x+2</m></cell>
              <cell>Point</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\frac{3}{4}(-2)+2=0.5</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(-2,0.5)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\frac{3}{4}(-1)+2=1.25</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(-1,1.25)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>0</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\frac{3}{4}(0)+2=2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(0,2)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\frac{3}{4}(1)+2=2.75</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(1,2.75)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\frac{3}{4}(2)+2=3.5</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(2,3.5)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>3</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\frac{3}{4}(3)+2=4.25</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(3,4.25)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>4</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\frac{3}{4}(4)+2=5</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(4,5)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="none">
              <cell><m>5</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\frac{3}{4}(5)+2=5.75</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(5,5.75)</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          <p>
            This table lets us plot the graph and identify a slope triangle that is easy to work
            with.
          </p>
          <image width="47%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                    xmin = -5,
                    ymin = -5,
                    xmax = 7,
                    ymax = 7,
                    ylabel={\(f(x)\)}
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain = -5:7] {3/4*x+2};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,0.5) (-1,1.25) (0,2) (1,2.75) (2,3.5) (3,4.25) (4,5) (5, 5.75)};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,2) (4,2)} node[pos=0.5,below] {\(4\)};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(4,2) (4,5)} node[pos=0.5,right] {\(3\)};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,2)} node[above left] {\((0,2)\)};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4,5)} node[above left] {\((4,5)\)};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <p>
            Since the slope triangle runs <m>4</m> units and then rises <m>3</m> units, the slope is
            <m>\frac{3}{4}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsection-comparing-slopes">
    <title>Comparing Slopes</title>
    <p>
      It's useful to understand when more than one line having different slopes appear on the same 
      coordinate system.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Effie, Ivan and Cleo are in a foot race. <xref ref="figure-foot-race"/> models the distance
        each has traveled in the first few seconds. Each runner takes a second to accelerate up to
        their running speed, but then runs at a constant speed. So they are then traveling with a
        constant rate of change, and the straight line portions of their graphs have a slope. Find
        each line's slope, and interpret its meaning in this context. What comparisons can you make
        with these runners?
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="figure-foot-race">
        <caption>A three-way foot race</caption>
        <image width="47%">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="footrace">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  xlabel={time (s)},
                  width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                  ylabel={distance (m)},
                  xmin=0,
                  xmax=5,
                  ymin=0,
                  ymax=15,
                  minor ytick={0,1,...,15},
                  minor xtick=,
                  xtick={0,1,...,5},
                  ytick={0,5,...,15},
                  axis line style={->},
                ]
                \addplot+[domain=1:5,->]{8/3*(x-1)+1} node[pos=0.5,sloped,below] {Effie};
                \addplot+[domain=1:5,->]{3.5*(x-1)+1} node[pos=0.5,sloped] {Ivan};
                \addplot+[domain=1:4.25,->]{4*(x-1)+2} node[pos=0.5,sloped,above] {Cleo};
                \addplot[firstcurve,-,domain=0:1]{x^(10/3)};
                \addplot[secondcurve,-,domain=0:1]{x^3.5};
                \addplot[thirdcurve,-,domain=0:1]{2*x^2};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        We will draw slope triangles to find each line's slope.
      </p>

      <figure>
        <caption>Find the Slope of Each Line</caption>
        <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" margins="0%">
          <image>
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="find-slope-of-each-line-1">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xlabel={\(t\)},
                    ylabel={distance (m)},
                    xmin=0,
                    xmax=5,
                    ymin=0,
                    ymax=15,
                    minor ytick={0,1,...,15},
                    minor xtick=,
                    xtick={0,1,...,5},
                    ytick={0,5,...,15},
                    width=0.32\orccaprintwidth,
                    axis line style={->},
                  ]
                  \addplot[firstcurve,domain=1:5,->]{8/3*(x-1)+1} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {Effie};
                  \addplot[firstcurve,-,domain=0:1]{x^(10/3)};
                  \addplot[soliddot]coordinates{(1,1) (4,9)};
                  \addplot[guideline]coordinates{(1,1) (4,1)} node[pos=0.5,above]{$3$ sec};
                  \addplot[guideline,->]coordinates{(4,1) (4,8.7)} node[pos=0.5,rotate=90,below]{$8$ meters};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>

          <image>
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="find-slope-of-each-line-2">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xlabel={\(t\)},
                    ylabel={distance (m)},
                    xmin=0,
                    xmax=5,
                    ymin=0,
                    ymax=15,
                    minor ytick={0,1,...,15},
                    minor xtick=,
                    xtick={0,1,...,5},
                    ytick={0,5,...,15},
                    width=0.32\orccaprintwidth,
                    axis line style={->},
                  ]
                  \addplot[secondcurve,domain=1:5,->]{3.5*(x-1)+1} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {Ivan};
                  \addplot[secondcurve,-,domain=0:1]{x^3.5};
                  \addplot[soliddot]coordinates{(1,1) (3,8)};
                  \addplot[guideline]coordinates{(1,1) (3,1)} node[pos=0.5,above]{$2$ sec};
                  \addplot[guideline,->]coordinates{(3,1) (3,7.7)} node[pos=0.5,rotate=90,below]{$7$ meters};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>

          <image>
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="find-slope-of-each-line-3">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xlabel={\(t\)},
                    ylabel={distance (m)},
                    xmin=0,
                    xmax=5,
                    ymin=0,
                    ymax=15,
                    minor ytick={0,1,...,15},
                    minor xtick=,
                    xtick={0,1,...,5},
                    ytick={0,5,...,15},
                    width=0.32\orccaprintwidth,
                    axis line style={->},
                  ]
                  \addplot[thirdcurve,domain=1:5,->]{4*(x-1)+2} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {Cleo};
                  \addplot[thirdcurve,-,domain=0:1]{2*x^2};
                  \addplot[soliddot]coordinates{(1,2) (3,10)};
                  \addplot[guideline]coordinates{(1,2) (3,2)} node[pos=0.5,above]{$2$ sec};
                  \addplot[guideline,->]coordinates{(3,2) (3,9.7)} node[pos=0.5,rotate=90,below]{$8$ meters};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </sidebyside>
      </figure>

      <p>
        Using <xref ref="equation-slope-definition" text="custom">the slope equation</xref>, we have:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Effie's slope is
              <m>\frac{8\,\text{m}}{3\,\text{s}}\approx2.666\,\frac{\text{m}}{\text{s}}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Ivan's slope is <m>\frac{7\,\text{m}}{2\,\text{s}}=3.5\,\frac{\text{m}}{\text{s}}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Cleo's slope is <m>\frac{8\,\text{m}}{2\,\text{s}}=4\,\frac{\text{m}}{\text{s}}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>

      <p>
        In a distance-over-time graph, the slope of a line represents speed. The slopes in these
        examples and the running speeds of these runners are measured in
        <quantity>
          <unit base="meter"/><per base="second"/>
        </quantity>.
        A relationship we can see is that the more steeply a line is slanted, the larger the slope
        is. This should make sense because for each passing second, the faster runner travels
        farther, making a slope triangle's height taller. This means that we can tell that Cleo is
        the fastest runner (and Effie is the slowest) just by comparing the slopes
        <m>4>3.5>2.666</m>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise xml:id="exercise-jogging-on-mt-hood" label="jogging-on-mt-hood">
      <title>Jogging on Mt.<nbsp/>Hood</title>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          $newUnits = [
            {name=>'feet',conversion=>{factor=>12*2.54/100,m=>1}},
            {name=>'foot',conversion=>{factor=>12*2.54/100,m=>1}},
            {name=>'ft',conversion=>{factor=>12*2.54/100,m=>1}},
            {name=>'hour',conversion=>{factor=>60*60,s=>1}},
            {name=>'hours',conversion=>{factor=>60*60,s=>1}},
            {name=>'hr',conversion=>{factor=>60*60,s=>1}},
            {name=>'hrs',conversion=>{factor=>60*60,s=>1}},
            {name=>'h',conversion=>{factor=>60*60,s=>1}},
          ];
          @s=(
            NumberWithUnits("500 ft/h",{newUnit=>$newUnits}),
            NumberWithUnits("0 ft/h",{newUnit=>$newUnits}),
            NumberWithUnits("-875 ft/h",{newUnit=>$newUnits})
          );
        </pg-code>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Kato is training for a race up the slope of Mt.<nbsp/>Hood, from Sandy to Government
            Camp, and then back. The graph models his elevation from his starting point as time
            passes. Find the slopes of the three line segments and interpret their meanings in this
            context.
          </p>
          <image width="47%">
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xlabel={time (h)},
                    ylabel={elevation (ft)},
                    xmin=0,
                    xmax=26,
                    ymin=0,
                    ymax=4000,
                    minor xtick={0,...,25},
                    xtick=,
                    ytick={0,500,...,3500},
                    minor ytick=,
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                    axis line style={->},
                  ]
                  \addplot[firstcurve,-] coordinates {(0,0) (7,3500) (19,3500) (23,0)};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is the slope of the first segment?
            </p>
            <p>
              <var name="$s[0]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              The first segment started at <m>(0,0)</m> and stopped at <m>(7,3500)</m>. This implies
              Kato started at the starting point, traveled <m>7</m> hours and reached a point
              <m>3500</m> feet higher in elevation from the starting point. The slope of the line is
              <md>
                \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{3500\,\text{ft}}{7\,\text{h}}=500\,\frac{\text{ft}}{\text{h}}
              </md>
              In context, Kato was gaining <m>500</m> feet in elevation per hour.              
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is the slope of the second segment?
            </p>
            <p>
              <var name="$s[1]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              What happened in the second segment, which started at <m>(7,3500)</m> and ended at
              <m>(19,3500)</m>? This implies he started this portion <m>3500</m> feet high, and
              didn't change elevation for <m>19</m> hours. Maybe some of that time he was running at
              a constant elevation, and some of that time he was resting.
              <md>
                \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{0\,\text{ft}}{12\,\text{h}}=0\,\frac{\text{ft}}{\text{h}}
              </md>
              In context, Kato was running but neither gaining nor losing elevation.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is the slope of the third segment?
            </p>
            <p>
              <var name="$s[2]" width="10" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              The third segment started at <m>(19,3500)</m> and stopped at <m>(23,0)</m>. This
              implies Kato started this part of his trip from <m>3500</m> feet high, traveled for
              <m>4</m> hours, and returned to the starting elevation. The slope of the line is
              <md>
                \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{-3500\,\text{ft}}{4\,\text{h}}=-875\,\frac{\text{ft}}{\text{h}}
              </md>
              In context, Kato was dropping in elevation by <m>875</m> feet per hour.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      Some important properties are demonstrated in <xref ref="exercise-jogging-on-mt-hood"/>.
    </p>

    <fact>
      <title>The Relationship Between Slope and Increase/Decrease</title>
      <p>
        In a linear relationship, as the <m>x</m>-value increases (in other words as you read its
        graph from left to right):
        <ul>
          <li>
            if the <m>y</m>-values increase (in other words, the line goes upward), its slope is              <idx><h>Positive slope</h></idx>
            positive.                                                                                         <idx><h>Slope</h><h>positive</h></idx>
          </li>
          <li>
            if the <m>y</m>-values decrease (in other words, the line goes downward), its slope is            <idx><h>Negative slope</h></idx>
            negative.                                                                                         <idx><h>Slope</h><h>negative</h></idx>
          </li>
          <li>
            if the <m>y</m>-values don't change (in other words, the line is flat, or horizontal),            <idx><h>Zero slope</h></idx>
            its slope is <m>0</m>.                                                                            <idx><h>Slope</h><h>zero</h></idx>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </fact>

    <p>
      These properties are summarized graphically in <xref ref="comparing-positive-negative-slope"/>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="comparing-positive-negative-slope">
      <caption></caption>
      <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" margins="0%">
        <figure xml:id="figure-positive-slope">
          <caption>Positive slope</caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="positive-slope">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    width=0.32\orccaprintwidth
                  ]
                  \addplot[firstcurve,domain=-6.25:7]{4/5*x-2};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <figure xml:id="figure-negative-slope">
          <caption>Negative slope</caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="negative-slope">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    width=0.32\orccaprintwidth
                  ]
                  \addplot[firstcurve,domain=-4.2:5.6]{-10/7*x+1};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <figure xml:id="figure-zero-slope">
          <caption>Zero slope</caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="zero-slope">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    width=0.32\orccaprintwidth
                  ]
                  \addplot[firstcurve,domain=-7:7]{2.35};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Finding Slope by Two Given Points</title>
    <p>
      Several times in this section we computed a slope by drawing a slope triangle. That's not
      necessary if you already have coordinates for two points on a line. In fact, sometimes it's
      not practical to draw a slope triangle. (For instance if you only have specific information
      about two points that are too close together to draw a triangle, or if you cannot clearly see
      precise coordinates where you might start and stop your slope triangle.) Here we will show
      how to find a line's slope without drawing a slope triangle.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Your neighbor planted a sapling from a local nursery in his front yard several years ago.
        Ever since then, it has been growing at a constant rate. By the end of the third year, the
        tree was
        <quantity>
          <mag>15</mag><unit base="foot" />
        </quantity>
        tall. By the end of the sixth year, the tree was
        <quantity>
          <mag>27</mag><unit base="foot" />
        </quantity>
        tall. What's the tree's rate of growth (<ie/><nbsp/>the slope)?
      </p>

      <p>
        We <em>could</em> sketch a graph for this scenario, and include a slope triangle. If we did
        that, it would look like:
      </p>

      <sidebyside widths="44% 50%" margins="0%">
        <figure>
          <caption>Height of a Tree</caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
              This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27). A slope triangle is
              drawn, starting at (3,15), passing (6,15), and ends at (6,27). The label from (3,15)
              to (6,15) is "6-3=3 years"; the label from (6,15) to (6,27) is "27-15=12 feet".
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="tree-height">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xlabel={years since planting},
                    ylabel={height (ft)},
                    xmin=0,
                    xmax=9,
                    ymin=0,
                    ymax=30,
                    minor ytick=,
                    minor xtick=,
                    xtick={0,1,...,8},
                    ytick={0,3,...,27},
                    clip=false,
                    width=0.44\orccaprintwidth,
                    axis line style={->},
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain = 1:6.5]{4*x+3};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(3,15)$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(6,27)$};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,15) (6,15)} node[pos=0.5,below] {$3$ years};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,15) (6,27)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90] {$12$ ft};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          By the slope triangle and <xref ref="equation-slope-definition"/> we have:
          <md>
            <mrow>\text{slope}=m\amp =\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\frac{12\,\text{ft}}{3\,\text{yr}}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =4\frac{\text{ft}}{\text{yr}}</mrow>
          </md>
          So the tree is growing at a rate of
          <quantity>
            <mag>4</mag><unit base="foot" /><per base="year" />
          </quantity>
        </p>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        But hold on. Did we really <em>need</em> this picture? The <q>rise</q> of <m>12</m> came
        from a subtraction of two <m>y</m>-values: <m>27-15</m>. And the <q>run</q> of <m>3</m> came
        from a subtraction of two <m>x</m>-values: <m>6-3</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Here is a picture-free approach. We know that after
        <quantity>
          <mag>3</mag><unit base="year" />
        </quantity>, the height is
        <quantity>
          <mag>15</mag><unit base="foot" />
        </quantity>.
        As an ordered pair, that information gives us the point <m>(3,15)</m> which we can label as
        <m>(\overset{x_1}{3},\overset{y_1}{15})</m>. Similarly, the background information tells us
        to consider <m>(6,27)</m>, which we label as <m>(\overset{x_2}{6},\overset{y_2}{27})</m>.
        Here, <m>x_1</m> and <m>y_1</m> represent the first point's <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-values,
        and <m>x_2</m> and <m>y_2</m> represent the second point's <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-values.
      </p>

      <p>
        Now we can write an alternative to <xref ref="equation-slope-definition"/>:
        <md number="yes" xml:id="equation-slope-formula">
          \text{slope}=m=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}
        </md>
        This is known as the <term>slope formula</term>. The following graphs help to understand why          <idx><h>Slope</h><h>formula</h></idx>
        this formula works. Basically, we are still using a slope triangle to calculate the slope.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="figure-slope-formula">
        <caption>Understanding the slope formula</caption>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
              This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27). A slope triangle is
              drawn, starting at (3,15), passing (6,15), and ends at (6,27). The label from (3,15)
              to (6,15) is "6-3=3 years"; the label from (6,15) to (6,27) is "27-15=12 feet".
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="understanding-slope-formula-1">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xlabel={years since planting},
                    ylabel={height (ft)},
                    xmin=0,
                    xmax=9,
                    ymin=0,
                    ymax=30,
                    minor ytick=,
                    minor xtick=,
                    xtick={},
                    ytick={},
                    clip=false,
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                    axis line style={->},
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain = 1:6.5]{4*x+3};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(3,15)$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(6,27)$};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,15) (6,15)} node[pos=0.5,below,align=left] {$6-3$\\${}=3$ years};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,15) (6,27)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90,align=left] {$27-15$\\${}=12$ ft};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>

          <image>
            <shortdescription>
              This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27). A slope triangle is
              drawn, starting at (3,15), passing (6,15), and ends at (6,27). The label from (3,15)
              to (6,15) is "x2-x1"; the label from (6,15) to (6,27) is "y2-y1".
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="understanding-slope-formula-2">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xmin=0,
                    xmax=9,
                    ymin=0,
                    ymax=30,
                    minor ytick=,
                    minor xtick=,
                    xtick={},
                    ytick={},
                    clip=false,
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                    axis line style={->},
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain = 1:6.5]{4*x+3};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(x_1,y_1)$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(x_2,y_2)$};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,15) (6,15)} node[pos=0.5,below,align=left] {$x_2-x_1$};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,15) (6,27)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90,align=left] {$y_2-y_1$};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </sidebyside>
      </figure>
    </example>

    <warning>
      <p>
        It's important to use subscript instead of superscript in the slope equation, because
        <m>y^2</m> means to take the number <m>y</m> and square it. When we use <m>y_2</m>, we are
        saying there are at least two <m>y</m>-values in the conversation, and <m>y_2</m> is the
        second of them.
      </p>
    </warning>

    <p>
      The beauty of the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="custom">slope formula</xref> is
      that to find a line's slope, we don't need to draw a slope triangle. Let's look at an example.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A line passes the points <m>(-5,25)</m> and <m>(4,-2)</m>. Find this line's slope.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          If you are new to this formula, it may help to label each number before using the formula.
          The two given points are:
          <md>
            (\overset{x_1}{-5},\overset{y_1}{25}) \qquad (\overset{x_2}{4},\overset{y_2}{-2})
          </md>
          Now apply the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="custom">slope formula</xref>:
          <md>
            <mrow>\text{slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-2-25}{4-(-5)}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-27}{9}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-3</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Note that we used parentheses when substituting negative numbers in <m>x_1</m> and
          <m>y_1</m>. This is a good habit to protect yourself from making errors with subtraction
          and double negatives.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise label="find-slope-from-coordinates">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("LimitedFraction");
          $m = Fraction(-5,6);
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A line passes through the points <m>(-18,14)</m> and <m>(18,-16)</m>. Find this line's
            slope.
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$m" width="10"/>
          </p>          
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To find a line's slope, we can use the slope formula:
            <md>\text{slope}=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</md>
            First, we mark which number corresponds to which variable in the formula:
            <md>(\overset{x_1}{-18},\overset{y_1}{14})\qquad(\overset{x_2}{18},\overset{y_2}{-16})</md>
            Now we substitute these numbers into the corresponding variables in the slope formula:
            <md>
              <mrow>\text{slope} \amp =\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
              <mrow> \amp =\frac{-16-14}{18-(-18)}</mrow>
              <mrow> \amp =\frac{-30}{36}</mrow>
              <mrow> \amp =\frac{-5}{6}</mrow>
            </md>
            So the line's slope is <m>-\frac56</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <reading-questions>
    <exercise label="how-to-calculate-rate-of-change-in-table">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a table of data with <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-values, explain how to calculate the
          rate of change from one row to the next.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="what-is-true-of-rate-of-change-in-straight-line-data">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If there is a table of data with <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-values, and the plot of all that
          data makes a straight line, what is true about the rates of change as you move from row to
          row in the table?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="what-does-sign-of-rate-of-change-mean">
      <statement>
        <p>
          What does it mean for a rate of change to be positive versus negative?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Have you memorized a formula for finding the slope between two points using their
          coordinates?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is an important thing to do with slope to make it more meaningful in an application
          problem?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Drawing a slope triangle can be helpful to think about slope. But what might happen that
          could make it impractical to draw a slope triangle?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </reading-questions>

  <exercises>
    <subexercises>
      <title>Skills Practice</title>
      <exercisegroup cols="3">
        <title>Rate of Change</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Find the rate of change between the two given points.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-point-coordinates">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-rate-of-change-point-coordinates">
            <pg-code>
              Context("Point");
              @a = random_subset(4, -9 .. 9);
              $A = Point((@a)[0,1]);
              $B = Point((@a)[2,3]);
              Context("LimitedFraction")->flags->set(allowMixedNumbers => 0, showMixedNumbers => 0);
              $m = Fraction($a[3] - $a[1], $a[2] - $a[0]);
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m><var name="$A"/></m> and <m><var name="$B"/></m> 
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$m" width="5"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-point-coordinates-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-rate-of-change-point-coordinates"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-point-coordinates-decimals">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-rate-of-change-point-coordinates-decimals">
            <pg-code>
              Context("Point");
              @a = map {$_/10} (random_subset(4, -99 .. 99));
              $A = Point((@a)[0,1]);
              $B = Point((@a)[2,3]);
              Context("Numeric");
              $m = Real(($a[3] - $a[1])/($a[2] - $a[0]));
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m><var name="$A"/></m> and <m><var name="$B"/></m> 
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$m" width="5"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-point-coordinates-decimals-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-rate-of-change-point-coordinates-decimals"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-point-coordinates-fractions">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-rate-of-change-point-coordinates-fractions">
            <pg-code>
              Context("LimitedFraction")->flags->set(allowMixedNumbers => 0, showMixedNumbers => 0);
              do {
                @a = random_subset(8, -9 .. -1, 1 .. 9);
                @x = map {Fraction($a[$_], $a[$_ + 1])} (0, 2);
              } until ($x[0] != $x[1]); 
              @y = map {Fraction($a[$_], $a[$_ + 1])} (4, 6);
              $A = Point($x[0], $y[0]);
              $B = Point($x[1], $y[1]);
              $m = ($y[1] - $y[0])/($x[1] - $x[0]);
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m><var name="$A"/></m> and <m><var name="$B"/></m> 
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$m" width="5"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-point-coordinates-fractions-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-rate-of-change-point-coordinates-fractions"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-graph">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-rate-of-change-graph">
            <pg-code>
              Context("Point");
              @a = random_subset(4, 1 .. 9);
              $A = Point((@a)[0,1]);
              $B = Point((@a)[2,3]);
              Context("LimitedFraction")->flags->set(allowMixedNumbers => 0, showMixedNumbers => 0);
              $m = Fraction($a[3] - $a[1], $a[2] - $a[0]);
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <image>
                <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        xmin=-1,
                        ymin=-1,
                        xmax=10,
                        ymax=10,
                        xtick=,
                        ytick=,
                        minor xtick={1,...,9},
                        minor ytick={1,...,9},
                        width=0.33\orccaprintwidth,
                      ]
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {$A $B};
                    \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
              </image>
              <p>
                <var name="$m" width="5"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-graph-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-rate-of-change-graph"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-graph-neg">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-rate-of-change-graph-neg">
            <pg-code>
              Context("Point");
              do {
                @a = random_subset(4, -5 .. 5)
              } until (min(@a) &lt; 0 &amp;&amp; max(@a) > 0);
              $A = Point((@a)[0,1]);
              $B = Point((@a)[2,3]);
              Context("LimitedFraction")->flags->set(allowMixedNumbers => 0, showMixedNumbers => 0);
              $m = Fraction($a[3] - $a[1], $a[2] - $a[0]);
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <image>
                <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        xmin=-6,
                        ymin=-6,
                        xmax=6,
                        ymax=6,
                        xtick=,
                        ytick=,
                        minor xtick={-5,...,5},
                        minor ytick={-5,...,5},
                        width=0.33\orccaprintwidth,
                      ]
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {$A $B};
                    \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
              </image>
              <p>
                <var name="$m" width="5"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-graph-neg-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-rate-of-change-graph-neg"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-graph-large">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-rate-of-change-graph-large">
            <pg-code>
              Context("Point");
              do {
                @a = random_subset(4, 10 .. 90);
                $A = Point((@a)[0,1]);
                $B = Point((@a)[2,3]);
                $D = Vector($B - $A);
              } until ($D->norm > 20);
              Context("LimitedFraction")->flags->set(allowMixedNumbers => 0, showMixedNumbers => 0);
              $m = Fraction($a[3] - $a[1], $a[2] - $a[0]);
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <image>
                <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        xmin=-10,
                        ymin=-10,
                        xmax=100,
                        ymax=100,
                        xtick=,
                        ytick=,
                        minor xtick=,
                        minor ytick=,
                        width=0.33\orccaprintwidth,
                      ]
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {$A} node[above] {$A};
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {$B} node[above] {$B};
                    \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
              </image>
              <p>
                <var name="$m" width="5"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-graph-large-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-rate-of-change-graph-large"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-table">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-rate-of-change-table">
            <pg-code>
              @x = num_sort(random_subset(5, 1 .. 9));
              @y = num_sort(random_subset(5, 1 .. 9));
              ($a,$b) = num_sort(random_subset(2, 0 .. 4));
              Context("LimitedFraction")->flags->set(allowMixedNumbers => 0, showMixedNumbers => 0);
              $m = Fraction($y[$b] - $y[$a], $x[$b] - $x[$a]);
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <tabular halign="right">
                <col right="medium"/>
                <col/>
                <row bottom="medium">
                  <cell><m>x</m></cell><cell><m>y</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m><var name="$x[0]"/></m></cell><cell><m><var name="$y[0]"/></m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m><var name="$x[1]"/></m></cell><cell><m><var name="$y[1]"/></m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m><var name="$x[2]"/></m></cell><cell><m><var name="$y[2]"/></m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m><var name="$x[3]"/></m></cell><cell><m><var name="$y[3]"/></m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m><var name="$x[4]"/></m></cell><cell><m><var name="$y[4]"/></m></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
              <p>
                From <m>x=<var name="$x[$a]"/></m> to <m>x=<var name="$x[$b]"/></m>.
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$m" width="5"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-table-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-rate-of-change-table"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="rate-of-change-table-large">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-rate-of-change-table-large">
            <pg-code>
              @x = num_sort(random_subset(5, 1 .. 99));
              @y = num_sort(random_subset(5, 1 .. 999));
              ($a,$b) = num_sort(random_subset(2, 0 .. 4));
              Context("LimitedFraction")->flags->set(allowMixedNumbers => 0, showMixedNumbers => 0);
              $m = Fraction($y[$b] - $y[$a], $x[$b] - $x[$a]);
